According to the above research, we can already know that Allston and Brighton are regarded as high-student residential density neighborhoods. Next, we obtained Land use types of the community through Boston Parcel data, including the number of residential households corresponding to each parcel, owner occupancy, total floor Numbers and other relevant data to explore the correlation between these factors. We also introduce the concept of BCR (building coverage ratio) as another way to calculate urban density and compare it with student population density.

Census mapping revealed that the high-density living areas of students in this community were concentrated on both sides of the axis of Commonwealth AVE, while the high student density was relatively rare in other regions, indicating that students and families in this community lived in distinct areas.

By parcel mapping, we find that the total number of residences along Commonwealth AVE is far higher than that of other areas, and the BCR of these areas is generally higher because there are a large number of condo or apartment 7 units above in these areas. Based on census mapping, it can be preliminarily concluded that the urban density of the community along the Commonwealth AVE in Allston is relatively high, and students tend to rent apartments close to Green line in the community.

To get a more accurate understanding of the rental situation in this region, we imported the total number of households of all types of housing, housing type, whether it is a lease, whether it is a residential land for comparative analysis. Through the diagram, we find that the number of apartments above 7 units in this community is the largest, followed by the residential condo and residential two families.

Among them, the apartment above 7 units are mainly rented for use, while the residential condo and residential two families are partially rented for their own use. On the whole, the rental market in this community accounts for about 66%, which is about twice that of the self-use housing market, indicating that the overall population flow rate in this community is also relatively frequent.
